{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519999"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.07,0.1,0.11,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58485"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1925"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58485"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine checkup. She is new to this practice as she recently moved and presents to establish care. She has a history of hypertension and takes blood pressure medications, but cannot recall the names. She has experienced mild ankle swelling for the past six months, which she recalls began soon after she started pharmacotherapy for her hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 142/96 mmHg. Her jugular venous pressure is not raised, her chest is clear on auscultation, and she has bilateral pitting oedema up to the ankles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely responsible for the patient\u0027s complaint?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amlodipine","Metoprolol","Hydrochlorothiazide","Lisinopril","Valsartan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E is a calcium channel blocker commonly used to treat hypertension, and it has a known side effect of peripheral oedema. Amlodipine works by relaxing and dilating the blood vessels, which helps lower blood pressure. However, this vasodilatory effect can also lead to increased capillary permeability, causing fluid to leak into the surrounding tissues, particularly in the lower extremities. This results in the characteristic leg swelling or oedema seen in some patients taking amlodipine. This does not typically respond to diuretics but may be managed through dose-reduction, switching to a different class of anti-hypertensive or adding a renin-angiotensin system inhibitor. Peripheral oedema affects approximately 10% of patients taking calcium channel blockers and has a variable onset from 4 weeks to over 6 months following medication initiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective beta-blocker used in the treatment of hypertension, heart failure, and rate control for atrial fibrillation. It rarely causes peripheral oedema. Metoprolol primarily works by reducing heart rate and cardiac output, rather than directly affecting blood vessel dilation. While metoprolol can cause bradycardia and hypotension, it is not typically associated with leg swelling or oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazide diuretic, often prescribed as an antihypertensive medication. It works by blocking the sodium-chloride channel in the distal convoluted tubule, leading to increased excretion of sodium and water. It can cause side effects such as orthostatic hypotension, hypercalcaemia, hypokalaemia, hyperlipidaemia, and hyperglycaemia. Apart from its primary function of volume loss, with time, hydrochlorothiazide has the ability to sustain blood pressure reduction by causing vasodilatation and reducing peripheral vascular resistance. However it is much less likely than a calcium channel blocker to produce dependent oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELisinopril\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor used to treat hypertension and heart failure. It works by inhibiting the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II, thereby reducing blood pressure. While ACE inhibitors can cause side effects such as dry cough and rarely angioedema, they are not typically associated with peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValsartan\u003C/strong\u003E is an angiotensin II receptor blocker (ARB) used to treat hypertension and heart failure. It works by blocking the action of angiotensin II on its receptor, leading to vasodilation and reduced blood pressure. Like ACE inhibitors, ARBs are not typically associated with peripheral oedema and are often used to treat oedema in heart failure patients. Valsartan may cause side effects such as dizziness or hyperkalaemia, but leg swelling is not a common side effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium channel blockers (CCBs) are associated with a substantial risk of peripheral oedema, including pedal oedema, which is the most common reason for its discontinuation."],"references":["Gabb, Genevieve M., et al. \u0022Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults\u20142016.\u0022 Medical Journal of Australia 205.2 (2016): 85-89.","Makani, Harikrishnaa; Bangalore, Sripalb; Romero, Jorgea; Htyte, Naya; Berrios, Ronaldo Sa; Makwana, Hetala; Messerli, Franz Ha. Peripheral edema associated with calcium channel blockers: incidence and withdrawal rate \u2013 a meta-analysis of randomized trials. Journal of Hypertension 29(7):p 1270-1280, July 2011. | DOI: 10.1097/HJH.0b013e3283472643"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-01T10:31:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T10:32:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5562"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58485"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app